#. type: Title #
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:11
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating a full LXD Server"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:16
msgid ""
"LXD is best described on the [official website](https://linuxcontainers.org/"
"lxd/introduction/), but think of it as a container system that provides the "
"benefits of virtual servers in a container, or a container on steroids."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:18
msgid ""
"It is very powerful, and with the right hardware and set up, can be "
"leveraged to run a lot of server instances on a single piece of hardware. If "
"you pair that with a snapshot server, you also have a set of containers that "
"you can spin up almost immediately in the event that your primary server "
"goes down."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:20
msgid ""
"(You should not think of this as a traditional backup. You still need a "
"regular backup system of some sort, like [rsnapshot](../../guides/backup/"
"rsnapshot_backup.md).)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:22
msgid ""
"The learning curve for LXD can be a bit steep, but this book will attempt to "
"give you a wealth of knowledge at your fingertips, to help you deploy and "
"use LXD on Rocky Linux."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:24
msgid ""
"For those wanting to use LXD as a lab environment on their own laptops or "
"workstations, see [Appendix A: Workstation Setup](30-appendix_a.md)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:25
#, no-wrap
msgid "Prerequisites And Assumptions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:33
msgid ""
"One Rocky Linux server, nicely configured. You should consider a separate "
"hard drive for ZFS disk space (you have to if you are using ZFS) in a "
"production environment. And yes, we are assuming this is a bare metal "
"server, not a VPS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:33
msgid ""
"This should be considered an advanced topic, but we have tried our best to "
"make it as easy to understand as possible for everyone. That said, knowing a "
"few basic things about container management will take you a long way."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:33
msgid ""
"You should be very comfortable at the command line on your machine(s), and "
"fluent in a command line editor. (We are using _vi_ throughout this example, "
"but you can substitute in your favorite editor.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:33
msgid ""
"You need to be an unprivileged user for the bulk of the LXD processes. "
"Except where noted, enter LXD commands as your unprivileged user. We are "
"assuming that you are logged in as a user named \"lxdadmin\" for LXD "
"commands. The bulk of the set up _is_, done as root until you get past the "
"LXD initialization. We will have you create the \"lxdadmin\" user later in "
"the process."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:33
msgid ""
"For ZFS, make sure that UEFI secure boot is NOT enabled. Otherwise, you will "
"end up having to sign the ZFS module in order to get it to load."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:33
msgid "We are using Rocky Linux-based containers for the most part."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "Synopsis"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 1: Install and Configuration** deals with the installation of the "
"primary server. In general, the proper way to do LXD in production is to "
"have both a primary server and a snapshot server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 2: ZFS Setup** deals with the setup and configuration of the ZFS. "
"ZFS is an open-source logical volume manager and file system created by Sun "
"Microsystems, originally for its Solaris operating system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 3: LXD Initialization and User Setup** Deals with the base "
"initialization and options. It also deals with the setup of our unprivileged "
"user that we will use throughout most of the rest of the process."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 4: Firewall Setup** deals with both `iptables` and `firewalld` "
"setup options, but we recommend that you use `firewalld`for all current "
"Rocky Linux versions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 5: Setting Up and Managing Images** describes the process for "
"installing OS images to a container and configuring them."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 6: Profiles** deals with adding profiles and applying them to "
"containers and particularly covers macvlan and its importance for IP "
"addressing on your LAN or WAN"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 7: Container Configuration Options** briefly covers some of the "
"basic configuration options for containers and offers some pros and cons for "
"modifying configuration options."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 8: Container Snapshots** details the snapshot process for "
"containers on the primary server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 9: The Snapshot Server** covers the setup and configuration of the "
"snapshot server and how to create the symbiotic relationship between the "
"primary and snapshot server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Chapter 10: Automating Snapshots** covers the automation of snapshot "
"creation and populating the snapshot server with new snapshots."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:46
msgid ""
"**Appendix A: Workstation Setup** not technically a part of the production "
"server documents, but offers a solution for people who want a simple way to "
"build a lab of LXD containers on their personal laptop or workstation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "Conclusions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:51
msgid ""
"You can use these chapters to effectively setup an enterprise-level primary "
"and snapshot LXD server. In the process, you will learn a great deal about "
"LXD, and we *have* touched on a lot of features. Just be aware that there is "
"much more to learn, and treat these documents as a starting point."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/00-toc.md:52
msgid ""
"The greatest advantage of LXD is that it is economical to use on a server, "
"allows you to spin up OS installs quickly, can be used for multiple stand-"
"alone application servers running on a single piece of bare metal, all of "
"which properly leverages that hardware for maximum use."
msgstr ""
